<h1 class="graf graf--h3">Richard Pearson DC: He Was Assaulted Again in His&nbsp;Groin.</h1>
<h4 class="graf graf--h4">The torture campaign continued with another electrocution to Richard Pearson&rsquo;s groin.</h4>
<p class="graf graf--p">Pearson is not as socially engaged as he used to be. The outgoing man with a smile and colorful clothes has retreated. Acquaintances often ask about his less cheerful disposition and the knitted hat that he wears. It is stuffed with aluminum foil. He would rather not discuss. He is not anti-social. He is in self-preservation mode. On the inside of his mind, he has found his happy place. He still loves the joy that he gets from talking with friends and strangers. He&rsquo;s made more friends with nature. Things are different now. There is the aluminum foil that he wears on his head. He was pinned several times. He stole a Sprite from a store without any conscious awareness of doing so. He returned it. There is the aluminum foil covering his groin area. He was electrocuted in his penis. Then, electrocuted again.</p>
<p class="graf graf--p">Back in the US, Pearson is selling art for a friend until he can save up enough money for a plane ticket. He is determined to leave the United States.</p>
<p class="graf graf--p">Pearson was seated a farther distance from his booth than usual &mdash; in the very back, outside of the tent. He noticed a 12- or 13-year-old white boy who kept staring at him. Every time Pearson looked up, the boy would stare from behind the art prints. Not stare as in accidental watching. Staring as in intentional and deliberate &mdash; stalk-ish. Pearson looked around the area, <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;What the hell is going on?&rdquo;</em> The boy continued.</p>
<p class="graf graf--p">Pearson had recalled that a woman on the Greyhound bus had done the same thing when he was leaving Plattsburgh, New York after his failed asylum attempt in Canada. Pearson boarded the bus at 1am. The woman in the seat in front of him kept looking back and staring. After the third stare, Pearson admonished her. She continued. She had to be coming from Canada. Plattsburgh was the first stop in the US.</p>
<p class="graf graf--p">Thirty minutes into the ride, Pearson noticed that someone would cough every time that he moved. He moved 2&ndash;3 additional times to verify. It was coming from different parts of the front of the bus. <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;Some sort of gang,&rdquo;</em> Pearson concluded. <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;It&rsquo;s probably the same gang that stalked me on Montreal streets. It&rsquo;s the reason why I left.&rdquo;</em> He moved a fourth time. He did the coughing himself. Immediately, the sound of a crushed bottle. They came prepared, he thought to himself.</p>
<p class="graf graf--p">When he arrived in New York for his layover, his teeth were extremely sensitive, as if he had gone to the dentist. <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;I bit into my breakfast sandwich at the terminal and felt like my teeth were about to fall out. It felt like an extreme tooth whitening.&rdquo;</em> Teeth whitening involves dehydrating the teeth, more or less, to remove stains, making them highly sensitive. He has had the procedure several times. Pearson recalled that a man had boarded at a stop with a very noisy device. He stored it in a bag. <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;It sounded like nothing I had heard of &mdash; metal on metal. It had the sound of an old, industrial fan.&rdquo;</em></p>
<p class="graf graf--p">At the market, Pearson thought of that moment when the boy kept staring. <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;Alert!&rdquo;</em> was his internal voice. Soon after, Pearson gets up from his seat to get away and goes in the pedestrian area in the front of the tent. Pearson recalls that a big white man called him over to ask about the price of a print. He then asks about the portability of the print. <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;Yes, you could roll it, then unroll it once you&rsquo;re home.&rdquo;</em> The man kept repeating the same question in different variations 3&ndash;4 times. The man had mentioned that he was flying. His accent struck Pearson as very strange. English with a very regional accent. It matched no US accent that he knew. It sounded slightly Midwestern with the vowel sounds, but with other unrecognizable textures. He was clearly from North America, but where?<em class="markup--em markup--p-em"> &ldquo;Canada!&rdquo;</em> But that conclusion came later.</p>
<p class="graf graf--p">Nearing the end of the conversation with the man, Pearson felt a strong pain in the lower part of his testicles. He hadn&rsquo;t connected that the boy and man were together. He was wearing foil, but that part wasn&rsquo;t covered. It stung. Painful. He initially thought that the foil between his pairs of underwear was rubbing it.</p>
<p class="graf graf--p">They leave. Pearson sat down. He&rsquo;s contemplative, <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;What just happened?&rdquo;</em></p>
<p class="graf graf--p">Pearson had been electrocuted again. He added it up. Boy staring. Same as the lady on the Greyhound bus. That machine. His sensitive teeth. Man with the strange accent repeating the same question. Pain in groin.</p>
<p class="graf graf--p">He chased after the family, taking the sidewalk. He would capture the image from their left. He caught up with them.</p>
<p class="graf graf--p">The man, his wife, the preteen, and a little girl were walking out of the market. The little girl saw Pearson. She tries to get the attention of her father who stared straight ahead. With Pearson right there, she doesn&rsquo;t see any alternative but to inaudibly whisper and point. She doesn&rsquo;t get his attention.</p>
