<p class="graf graf--p graf--startsWithDoubleQuote">&ldquo;Canadians!&rdquo;, Pearson figured. <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;The man followed me here or was here already and now outbound after an assault.&rdquo; </em>Pearson figured that there was no point reporting it. After his first incident, the police in Silver Spring, Maryland just laughed at him. He won&rsquo;t be humiliated again.</p>
<p class="graf graf--p">Pearson concluded that the man stalked him to the market just to electrocute his penis. He doesn&rsquo;t know if it was the man, his family, or another unseen co-conspirator, but the pain was not incidental to the other facts. <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;This is the fallout of a campaign that targeted me in the first place. It was designed to be decentralized, so now I have these people doing all sorts of things to me. It&rsquo;s just awful. Now, I have been assaulted at least twice in my penis!&rdquo;</em></p>
<p class="graf graf--p">After the first electrocution, Pearson had wondered if he had damage. He had not recalled any stimulation in his penis since the incident. It caused alarm, though he eventually settled on several thoughts &mdash; he was fleeing the US to Canada, was in a hyper-emotional state, and did not have privacy. He needed to find out. <a class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" href="https://medium.com/@psyoper/us-torture-victim-sees-no-sexual-privacy-surveillance-foot-stomping-dragging-chairs-and-386701766064" target="_blank" data-href="https://medium.com/@psyoper/us-torture-victim-sees-no-sexual-privacy-surveillance-foot-stomping-dragging-chairs-and-386701766064">His solo activity in the hotel while waiting for his bus in Plattsburgh, New York was driven by theory-testing. In this essay, he discusses how occupants in the room above began running frantically when he began a video.</a> This is the emotional toil of torture. A man, having been electrocuted in his penis, wants to know if his parts still work, so he conducts an experiment on himself.</p>
<p class="graf graf--p">Pearson cherishes his homosexuality, viewing it as a gift. Though, the homophobic violence and insults have worn on him emotionally. <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;They have used this conditioning using electromagnetic violence to do things to my body. It&rsquo;s just so awful. I don&rsquo;t cry about the other stuff. I cry about this because this is who I am. The way that God made me. Since I was 16, I have loved myself just as I am. They are literally trying to colonize my body.&rdquo; </em>Pearson believes that God &mdash; Heavenly Mother and Heavenly Father &mdash; brings about justice. Pearson leaves it in God&rsquo;s hands for the restoration of justice. He is upset, but not angry or vengeful. Those are time wasters.</p>
<p class="graf graf--p">Pearson has noted that the <a class="markup--anchor markup--p-anchor" href="https://medium.com/@menvell.artist/a-stranger-electrocuted-me-in-my-penis-in-maryland-73d2c4aa9dbf" target="_blank" data-href="https://medium.com/@menvell.artist/a-stranger-electrocuted-me-in-my-penis-in-maryland-73d2c4aa9dbf">first electrocution in his penis was homophobic violence &mdash; a hate crime</a>. He&rsquo;s also noted that homophobic attacks have increased. A Black urban male made the most vulgar comment as Pearson passed, <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;Maybe he will slide into some pu**y. There is only but so much a** he can watch.&rdquo; </em>It revealed two things. Pearson&rsquo;s sexual privacy was severely breached and that there were things being done to his body.&nbsp;</p>
<p class="graf graf--p">Pearson knew it. His body was acting funny for no reason at all. It wasn&rsquo;t his normal arousal, which started in head. <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;You have to understand how this works. The penis does not have a mind of its own, ok? It starts in the brain. I really don&rsquo;t like to talk about the harms, but these people are the epitome of evil. These are the same people who appeal to justice when it&rsquo;s convenient for them but engage in such violence against a gay man. My suspicion is that it had been happening for years. These weapons are proliferating. If a young, unemployed Black urban male standing on a corner, spewing homophobic insults, has access to or knows people who have access these weapons, then we are talking a severe threat to public safety and human rights.&rdquo; </em>Pearson does not think that he is the only gay man under attack. He suspects at least four gay men in the last year. Pearson vaguely elaborates, <em class="markup--em markup--p-em">&ldquo;There is something deeper happening.&rdquo;</em></p>
<p class="graf graf--p">Pearson has little or no legal recourse in the US legal system. He could spend the next 7&ndash;10 chasing vanishing ghosts only to lead to a legal dead-end, but he&rsquo;d rather not. The government needs to step in.</p>
